I also agree that my initial hack to stop the leak by limiting the validator map size to 50 is not shippable solution.  Is there any chance to make the limit more meaningful?  For example, if we can find the containing EPackage size (# of classifiers defined in the EPackage) inexpensively , we may use it as the limit of validatorMap, like

public static Validator getValidator(EClass containingClass, EStructuralFeature eStructuralFeature)
  {
    if (eStructuralFeature == null)
    {
      return NULL_VALIDATOR;
    }
    else
    {
      BasicExtendedMetaData.EStructuralFeatureExtendedMetaData.Holder holder = 
        (BasicExtendedMetaData.EStructuralFeatureExtendedMetaData.Holder)eStructuralFeature;
      BasicExtendedMetaData.EStructuralFeatureExtendedMetaData extendedMetaData = holder.getExtendedMetaData();
      if (extendedMetaData == null)
      {
        // For the extended meta data to be created.
        //
        ExtendedMetaData.INSTANCE.getName(eStructuralFeature);
        extendedMetaData = holder.getExtendedMetaData();
      }
      Map validatorMap = extendedMetaData.getValidatorMap();
      Validator result = (Validator)validatorMap.get(containingClass);
      if (result == null)
      {
        limit = eStructuralFeature.getEType().getEPackage().getEclassifiers().size() + 1; // I am not sure if this is the right and the quickest way of getting the number classes in a package.
        if (validatorMap.size()< limit)  
            validatorMap.put(containingClass, result = new BasicValidator(containingClass, eStructuralFeature));
        else 
            result = new BasicValidator(containingClass, eStructuralFeature);
      }
      return result;
    }
  }

Another suggestion is that FeatureValidator variable is initialized actively in BasicFeatureMap.  Given that FeatureMapUtil.getValidator() may cause leak and may not be cheap (a BasicValidator object created may be created), I think it is worthwhile to defer its initialize to the first use.  It is used only in validate() method call.  Search the trace, I see BasicFeatureMap created 6 times, but validate() only called 3 times.  Validate() is called on the path causing the mem leak in our benchmark.  So this will not help our usage scenario.  But it may help other use cases.

public class BasicFeatureMap extends EDataTypeEList implements FeatureMap.Internal
{
  protected final FeatureMapUtil.Validator featureMapValidator = null;

  public BasicFeatureMap(InternalEObject owner, int featureID)
  {
    super(Entry.class, owner, featureID);

    featureMapValidator = FeatureMapUtil.getValidator(owner.eClass(), getEStructuralFeature());
  }
  protected Object validate(int index, Object object)
  {
    Object result = super.validate(index, object);
    EStructuralFeature eStructuralFeature = ((Entry)object).getEStructuralFeature();
    if (featureMapValidator == null) 
        featureMapValidator = FeatureMapUtil.getValidator(owner.eClass(), getEStructuralFeature());
    if (!eStructuralFeature.isChangeable() || !featureMapValidator.isValid(eStructuralFeature))
    {
      throw 
        new RuntimeException
          ("Invalid entry feature '" + eStructuralFeature.getEContainingClass().getName() + "." + eStructuralFeature.getName() + "'");
    }
    return result;
  }


